Ratio of all systems combined OPEB ADC to governmental fund revenues. If a local government has multiple plans, all ADC amounts are added together to calculate the ratio to governmental fund revenues.
Interfund accounts receivable, net of allowance. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amount of accumulation of periodic credits made to record the expiration of the estimated service life of buildings.
Program expenses for housing and community development services, which are incremental revenues derived from that specific program, generated from sources other than the tax base.

Facility held for productive use including, but not limited to, office, production, storage and distribution facilities and any addition, improvement, or renovation to the structure, for example, but not limited to, interior masonry, interior flooring, electrical, and plumbing, reported net of accumulated depreciation.
In a special funding situation, the employer's proportionate share of the collective pension liability.

Amount of liabilities for materials and services evidenced by vouchers which have been pre-audited and signed by the proper authority approving the liability. Debit upon payment of vouchers; credit for amounts approved for payment.
Increase (decrease) in customer deposits payable.
Public and private contributions. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Allowance for refunds, modified accrual.
Information about expenditures for cultural activities.
Amount Authorized – Voter Approved Overrides. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about operating expenses for recreation and culture.
Expenditures for activities concerned with buying or constructing buildings. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Used to group information reported on Form F65.

Represents cash and cash equivalents, restricted. Restricted assets should be reported when restrictions on asset use change the nature or normal understanding of the availability of the asset. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Due from other government entities that the reporting entity does not separately disclose in the same statement or note for amounts due in more than one year. This account is debited when the amount due the local unit from other government entities is determined; credited when payments are received.

Represents the portion of other fund balance that is constrained by the government’s intent to be used for specific purposes (but are neither restricted nor committed). Sometimes a fund’s entire fund balance will be assigned, but more often only a portion will be, so this may take additional analysis. These accounts should be pointed off with individual assignments into separate sub-accounts. Must be used with a typed dimension to indicate a fact which is custom created for that reporting entity.
Revenue from a State source that is sent by a state or local agency other than State Department of Education.
Timber rights.

Revenues earned from health and welfare, child care, family division of circuit court, used n the General Fund or the Child Care Fund. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenditures for the medical examination, treatment, and care of sick or injured firefighters, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amount of increase (decrease) in cash and cash equivalents. Cash and cash equivalents are the amount of currency on hand as well as demand deposits with banks or financial institutions. Includes other kinds of accounts that have the general characteristics of demand deposits. Also includes short-term, highly liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash and so near maturity that the investments present insignificant risk of changes in value because of changes in interest rates. Includes effect from exchange rate changes.
Information about school district revenue, federal revenue.
Expenses for public works that qualify as Non-Act 51.

Revenue from tuition from other school districts and Board of Cooperative Educational Services (BOCES) within the state for instructional services provided This account includes: revenue received from the state Department of Education for out-of-district placed pupils and from other districts for excess costs for special education students; and, revenue received for tuition from other state public school districts and BOCES. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenditures for non instructional services. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about benefits expenses for OPEB and pension.
Used to identify the name of the issuer of the derivative instrument for a non pension investment portfolio.
Charges for services - plan review fees. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amount of cash restricted as to withdrawal or usage. Restrictions may include legally restricted deposits held as compensating balances against short-term borrowing arrangements, contracts entered into with others, or company statements of intention with regard to particular deposits. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amount of advances to component units where such advances are not due within a year. Debit for the amounts advanced by the local unit to another unit credit for the repayment of any portion of such advances.

Revenue earnings from interest income, is any income made from lending borrowers money. Regular taxable interest is taxed as ordinary income, just like an individual retirement account (IRA) or retirement plan distribution.1 This means interest income is added to the taxpayer’s other ordinary income.
Cash payments to other suppliers for other goods or services.
Furniture and fixtures.
Food service revenues which are not reimbursable under the provisions of the National School Lunch Program. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Revenue earned from reimbursement of guardian ad litem services.
Information about expenses for lottery activities.
Revenue earned from fines. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Cash received from special assessment levied.
Information about derivative instruments.
Expenditures associated with operations. Reported on a modified accrual basis.

Investments in subsidiaries, which is the amounts pertaining to a security or other asset that (a) a government holds primarily for the purpose of income or profit and (b) has a present service capacity based solely on its ability to generate cash or to be sold to generate cash.
Fees from other school districts and BOCES within the state for transporting students to and from school or activities. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Proceeds from bond and/or note issuance including premiums on bonds or notes, and bond or insurance recoveries.

Expenditures for activities concerned with paying, transporting, exchanging and maintaining goods and services for the school district. Included are the fiscal and internal services necessary for operating the school district. Include the Chief Business Official and the activities of the Chief Business Official here, unless reportable under 2501. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Revenues from interest and dividends.
Expenditures for convention center services. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
The portion of special assessments receivable estimated not to be collectible. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
The portion of special assessments receivable estimated not to be collectible. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about nonoperating revenues and expenses.
Expenditures for Recreation and Culture, Library services. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Revenue from a federal source that is sent by a state or local agency other than the State Department of Education.
Yard and storage equipment.

Revenues earned after the property tax foreclosure process within the delinquent tax revolving fund. The act states the foreclosing governmental unit must deposit the proceeds from the sale of tax delinquent property into a "restricted account" created for each year a property sale is held. The restricted accounts should be established within the Delinquent Property Tax Revolving Fund based on the year of the sale. This activity (Activity # 254--Delinquent Tax Property Sales) is used to record the sale proceeds and the authorized expenditures of the proceeds. When the forfeited property is sold, the proceeds from the sale should be recorded in the Delinquent Property Tax Revolving Fund under revenue account "Charge for Services-Sales." Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenditures for convention center services.

Revenue earned from sales and use tax levied which is defined as a tax on the storage, use, or consumption of a taxable item or service on which no sales tax has been paid. Use tax is a complementary or compensating tax to the sales tax and does not apply if the sales tax was charged.
State grants used for crime victims rights.
Used to group information about derivatives.

Revenue earned from probate court, used on the General Fund of a county. Reflects statutory revenue for estate cases, adoptions, and other probate matters. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

A trademark is a type of intellectual property consisting of a recognizable sign, design, or expression which identifies products or services of a particular source from those of others, although trademarks used to identify services are usually called service marks.

Expenditures associated with special operations which is for tasks other than standard firefighting operations. Special operations may include water rescue, extrication, hazardous materials, and other operations requiring specialized training. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about Cash Equivalents held with others.
Information about nonoperating revenues.
Premium and discounts.
State grants for the reimbursement of costs associated with special elections.
Other investments which the reporting entity does not separately disclose. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Trademarks.

Expenses for parks supervision, used on the General Fund or on a Park/Recreation Fund. It reflects such expenses as salaries and wages, supplies, materials, and equipment necessary to supervise park operation or recreation programs of a local unit.

Investment costs applicable to the required reporting of Fiduciary activities under GASB Statement No. Reported on a modified accrual basis. 84. Reported on a modified accrual basis. This will normally be reported as a negative amount, to be used with the reported investment earnings to generate a Net investment earnings amount for reporting purposes for Fiduciary funds only. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about expenditures for all other government activities.
Type of derivative instrument held by the government at the end of the fiscal year.
Expenditures for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for General Pre‐School Education. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Revenue from royalties.
Revenues earned from the transportation system used on the General Fund or Transportation System Fund. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Services purchased to operate, repair, maintain, and rent property owned or used by the government. These services are performed by persons other than government employees. While a product may or may not result from the transaction, the primary reason for the purchase is the service provided. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses associated with public safety services..

Amount before accumulated depreciation of equipment commonly used in offices and stores that have no permanent connection to the structure of a building or utilities. Examples include, but are not limited to, desks, chairs, tables, and bookcases.
Receipts from property and other taxes levied specifically to finance the construction, acquisition, or improvement of capital assets.
Expenditures associated with fire marshal. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Parking decks and lots.

Amounts paid for services rendered by organizations or personnel not on the payroll of the government (separate from Professional and Technical Services or Property Services). While a product may or may not result from the transaction, the primary reason for the purchase is the service provided. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Grants, contributions and donations earned from other sources which can include nonprofit organizations and for-profit businesses that provide grants or other types of funding assistance.

Infrastructure assets are long-lived capital assets that normally are stationary in nature and normally can be preserved for a significantly greater number of years than most capital assets. Examples of infrastructure assets include roads, bridges, tunnels, drainage systems, water and sewer systems, dams, and lighting systems.

Used on the General Fund of all local units of government. Its use is mandatory. It reflects such expenditures as building maintenance, grounds maintenance, janitor service, fuel, utilities, etc., for a county courthouse, city, village, or township hall, or other municipal office building. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Cost of derivative instrument which is held by the government at the end of the fiscal year.
Deposits and short-term, highly liquid investments with fiscal and escrow and other agents. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Revenue earned from tuition from other school districts and Board of Cooperative Educational Services (BOCES) within the state for instructional services provided This account includes: revenue received from the state Department of Education for out-of-district placed pupils and from other districts for excess costs for special education students; and, revenue received for tuition from other state public school districts and BOCES.
Other cash flows from investing activities.
Information about grants, contributions and donations.
Fees generated by providing transportation services. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses for health and welfare.
Computer equipment.

Revenue earned from supplemental payments from Medicaid payments to providers that are separate from and in addition to the payments for services rendered to Medicaid enrollees. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Market value of derivative instrument which is held by the government at the end of the fiscal year.
Information about nonoperating expenses.
Liabilities and deferred inflows of resources. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Nonoperating revenues from connection fees.

Amounts paid to employees of the school district in either temporary or permanent positions for work performed in addition to the employee’s regular work assignment. Additional/extra duty pay/stipend includes compensation for such assignments as coaching, cocurricular activity sponsorship, supplemental pay for curriculum development, for night school, etc.
Net (Expense) Revenue for non instructional services.
Expenses for parks and recreation.
Revenue for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for Other General Education.

Amounts owed by a local unit to the State. Detailed sub-accounts should be maintained if more than one advance is received. Debit for any subsequent decreases (repayments) of the advance amounts; credit for amounts of advances received and for any subsequent increases. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Increase (decrease) in accounts receivable and lease receivable.

Revenue internal to the district which is generated by charging user fees to other funds and programs for warehouse services. This code may be used only in an internal service fund or when internal service activities are involved.
Net OPEB liability (i.e., Fiduciary Net Position) calculated using a healthcare cost trend rate that is 1-percentage-point lower than the assumed healthcare cost trend rate.
Reflects the portion of fund balance that is not in spendable form for endowments.
Amounts reported for deferred inflows that are tied to leases. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
In a special funding situation, the nonemployer contributing entities' total proportionate share of the collective net OPEB liability.

Other restricted components of net position, which the reporting entity does not separately disclose in the same statement. Must be used with a typed dimension to indicate a fact which is custom created for that reporting entity.

Expenditures for welfare-related services including administration, institutional care, direct assistance, intergovernmental welfare payments, and vendor welfare payments. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses for community development block grants (CDBG).

Short-term amounts due from a retirement system fund within the local government's reporting entity. It represents amounts owed for goods and services rendered to a particular fund by another fund in the government reporting entity or for interfund loans that are due within one year. An offsetting liability must be recorded in the fund from which the payment is due. This account is debited when the amounts owed from other funds are determined; credited when amounts are received from other funds.
The balance of bonds payable due. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
The capital outlay related to the acquisition of a lease under GASB Statement No. 88.
Amounts paid to individuals who no longer are employed by the district. This includes early retirement incentive plan payments.
Net (Expense) Revenue for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for Other General Education.
Revenue earned from all other services rendered charges.

Net (Expense) Revenue for activities concerned with making nonpermanent improvements or enhancements to building sites. These improvements include fencing, walkways, tunnels and temporary landscaping.
Taxes levied for other governments that are to be collected and distributed to the other governments.
Net OPEB liability (i.e., Fiduciary Net Position) calculated using a healthcare cost trend rate that is 1-percentage-point higher than the assumed healthcare cost trend rate.
Bond premiums payable, amount due within one year.
Costs incurred for bond issuance and recognition of a portion of the unamortized bond discount for the reporting period.
Other financing options, current.
Contributions to other governments. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about miscellaneous other revenues.
Earnings on endowments and permanent fund investments. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Other financing sources (uses) which the reporting entity does not separately disclose in the same statement or note. It includes a limited number of special transactions that are used to account for non-operating revenues or receipts and expenditures or disbursements . Included in this financial reporting category are operating transfers (inflow) and proceeds from debt transactions. Used to report amounts on a modified accrual basis.
Bond premium, principal due within one year.
Other restricted components of net position which consists of restricted assets reduced by liabilities and deferred inflows of resources related to those assets.

Expenses for court of equity which is a type of court that hears cases involving remedies other than monetary damages, such as injunctions, writs, or specific performance and a court of law, only hears cases involving monetary damages.
Expenses for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Agriculture.

Net (Expense) Revenue for outlays of governmental funds are not properly classified as expenditures, but still require budgetary or accounting control. These are classified as Other Uses. These include debt service payments (principal and interest) and certain transfers of moneys from one fund to another.
The date of experience studies on which the significant assumptions used in the actuarial valuation are based.
Amount of accrued interest and penalties on taxes receivable, net of allowance for uncollectible amounts. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amounts held for certificates of participation (COP) which allows investors to participate in a pro-rata share of a lease-financing agreement. A lease-financing agreement is used by a municipality or local government to acquire real property.
Expenses associated with sanitary sewer services.

Expenses that include activities designed to provide support services for the institution's primary missions of instruction, public service, and research. Academic support includes the operation of the library, educational media services, instructional materials center, and academic computing used in the learning process. Some other activities include tutoring, learning skills centers, and reading and writing centers, that can be reported in the “2090 Other” category. It also includes Expenses for all equipment, materials, supplies, and costs that are necessary to support this function.
Other salaries.
Increase (decrease) in deferred inflows, leases.
Expenses associated with medical care facilities.

Amounts owed by a local unit of government to another local unit. Debit for any subsequent decreases (repayments) of the advance amounts; credit for amounts of advances received and for any subsequent increases. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
A description of the OPEB Plan Mortality Rate Table used in the actuarial valuation.
Revenue for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Agriculture.

Expenses for activities concerned with providing community services to students, staff or other community participants. Examples of this program are the operation of a community swimming pool and a recreation program for the elderly, a child care center, etc.
Amount, excluding unamortized premium (discount) and debt issuance cost, of long-term debt due in more than one year. Excludes lease obligation.
Amounts held for lease-financing agreement which is used by a municipality or local government to acquire real property.

Other revenues not including interest and rents, fine and forfeits, charges for services, government grants and contributions, licenses and permits, special assessments, taxes, reimbursements, sale of capital assets, public and private contributions, refunds and rebates, and miscellaneous other revenue.
Cost incurred for other lottery costs.
Cost incurred for lottery prize awards.
The interest payments on matured debt and loans that are due and payable within the normal operating cycle. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Allowance for amounts owed to the local government unit that are held by the Treasurer. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
OPEB Plan contribution deficiency (excess).
Expenses associated with public utilities.
Net (expense) revenue used for crime victims' rights.
State retirement plan contributions.
Net OPEB Liability as a percentage of covered payroll.
Reflects the portion of fund balance that is not in spendable form for encumbrances.
Allowance for land contracts receivable due in more than one year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Grants, contributions and donations from state governmental entities. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Expenditures for recreation and culture activities, used on the General Fund or Park/Recreation Fund. It reflects expenditures incurred in park facilities, recreation programs, and cultural programs within a local unit. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Cost of materials and services rendered.
Changes in pension liability due to changes in actuarial assumptions and other inputs.
Net Changes in Total OPEB Liability.
Amounts owed to the local government unit from services performed, net of allowance for uncollectible accounts.
Information about short term debt.

Amount of monies on deposit in savings accounts under the control of the official or agent designated as custodian. This account is debited when money is deposited in a savings account; credited when money is withdrawn from a savings account, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Contributions from local government units for transit. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

The portion of special assessments receivable estimated not to be collectible and that is due in more than one year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenditures for fire department training. Used on the General Fund or Fire Fund of local units of government that have such an activity reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses for operations and maintenance.
Information about tax anticipation notes.
Revenues earned from services rendered to other units or other departments. Used in the General Fund of a local unit of government. Reported on a modified accrual basis.

Revenues earned from friend of the court, used on the General Fund or Friend of the Court Fund or both funds of a county. Its use is mandatory. Reflects revenue such as support fees. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amounts owed to the local government unit from services performed.
State grants for drunk driving case flow assistance. Used for amounts reported on a modified accrual basis.
Allowance for loans and notes receivable estimated not to be collectible, due in more than one year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Revenue from property taxes. Property taxes are ad-valorem taxes levied on an assessed valuation of real property. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Changes in Net Pension Liability due to pension plan administrative expenses.
Interfund accounts receivable, net of allowance.
The amount of amortization expense recognized in the current period.

Tax Anticipation Note (TAN) is a type of municipal bond issues to finance a current operation or project before the issuer receives tax returns. In effect, the issuing government uses the following year's tax revenue to repay the tax anticipation note.

Amount of the portion of tax anticipation notes or other notes or loans to be paid by the local unit. A note payable is an unconditional written promise signed by the maker (authorized local unit officials) to pay a certain sum of money on demand or at a fixed or determinable time either to the bearer or to the order of a person designated therein. Debit for payments made on such notes; credit for the number of notes to be paid during the current year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Any other changes in net pension liability that's considered to be individually significant.
Allowance for loans receivable, due in more than one year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Interfund accounts receivable.
Information about all other purposes.

Employer’s required contributions to the OPEB plan for the reporting period, and separate liabilities to the OPEB plan that arise in the reporting period (for example, for amounts assessed to an individual employer upon joining a cost-sharing OPEB plan).

Expenditures for grand jury, used on the General Fund of any unit responsible for the expenditures incurred by a grand jury. Expenditures include legal fees, consultant fees, travel, supplies, etc. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Depletion, depreciation, and amortization expense recognized in the current period.

Housing assistance payments (HAP) for the Housing Choice Voucher (HCV) or similar type program paid or accrued to the owners of dwelling units leased to eligible families. Also included are HAP related expenses such as contributions to FSS escrow accounts, utility reimbursements, and mortgage payments paid using HAP subsidy for a HCV homeownership program. In addition this account includes, where applicable, HAP payments paid or accrued to owners for vacancies during and after rent-up pursuant to a housing assistance payments contract, and HAP payments paid or accrued to owners for reimbursement pursuant to the provisions of the housing assistance contract for any unpaid rent or damages caused by the tenants.
Amount of customer deposits payable in more than one year, and that are payable from restricted assets.
Information about all other state aid grants.
Allowance for notes receivable due in more than one year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
This account is used to record amounts owed to the local government unit for services performed but not yet billed, net of allowance for uncollectible accounts.
Any special assessment that is assessed on a community-wide basis, such an Act 33 public safety millage, should be reported as a tax. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
All other purpose long term debt which includes general obligation bonds, revenue bonds, unlimited tax bonds, limited tax bonds, notes payable and all other debt.
Revenue earned from other general activities. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amount due to others payable in more than one year, and that are payable from restricted assets.
Allowance for inter governmental receivable, due in more than one year, estimated not to be collectible. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Benefit payments made by the pension plan.
Information about all other debt.
This account is used to record amounts owed to the local government unit for services performed but not yet billed.

Revenues earned from sanitation services, for example sewerage charges, street sanitation, and refuse collection charges. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Other deferred outflows of resources. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Costs incurred for services directly related to meeting resident needs and supporting a wholesome living environment including employee salaries and benefits.
Record all other debt instruments with an original term of more than one year. Does not include general obligation bonds, revenue bonds, notes payable, unlimited tax bonds or limited tax bonds.
Information about Proprietary Funds, Statement of Net Position.

Not elsewhere classified fees and other revenue recorded based on estimates or specific contractual terms as transactions occur or services are rendered, provided that persuasive evidence exists, the price to the customer is fixed or determinable and collectability is reasonably assured, which have not yet been received as of the balance sheet date, net of allowance for uncollectible amounts.
Expenses associated with building authority.

Other expenditures which the reporting entity does not separately disclose in the same statement or note. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis. Must be used with a typed dimension to indicate a fact which is custom created for that reporting entity.
Information about advances, noncurrent.
Used to collect information on the statement of operations.
Net (expense) revenue associated with Debt service.
Allowance for inter governmental receivable.

Amounts due from due from townships for work performed on roads under agreement signed by the township and the road commission. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenditures for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for General Middle/Junior High School Education. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Indicates if the unit is a primary government (County, Township, City, Village). If it is, report as TRUE; If it is not, report as FALSE.
Program revenues used for equipment and equipment rental, which are incremental revenues derived from that specific program, generated from sources other than the tax base.
All revenue generated from taxes. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about accounts receivable, noncurrent.
Program revenues used for homestead, which are incremental revenues derived from that specific program, generated from sources other than the tax base.
Information about Funds Balances Restricted.
Table used to capture information about the OPEB Plans.
The portion of interest receivable estimated not to be collectible.
Amounts owed to the local government unit from any source. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Net (expense) revenue court from building inspection fees.
Information about special assessment revenues.
Revenue from a federal source that comes direct from the federal government. Reported on a modified accrual basis.

Revenue earned from shared revenue which is a government unit’s apportioning of part of its tax income to other units of government. For example, provinces or states may share revenue with local governments, or national governments may share revenue with provinces or states.
Information about notes and loans receivable.
Net (expense) revenue associated with public schools services.
Net (expense) revenue associated with depreciation.
Used for identifiers for OPEB Plans.
Fund Balance, restricted for excise tax revenue.
The portion of personal property taxes levied which have become due but have not become delinquent.
Prepaid pool contribution, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses associated with unemployment compensation.
Revenue from tuition from welfare agencies and private sources for educational services provided. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amount of premium and discount on issuance of bonds.
Information about all other sales, use and admission fees.
Net (expense) revenue associated with cost of issue of bonds and securities.
Information about special assessments receivable, noncurrent.
Information about Funds Balances Committed.
The portion of land contracts due and payable during the current fiscal year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Transfer to escrow for bond refunding.
The portion of property taxes receivable estimated not to be collectible.
Net (expense) revenue associated with cemetery services.
Used to collect information about OPEB Plans.
Amount of fee or grant for services provided to a number of people, such that the amount paid is determined by the number of patients, reported net of reinsurance expense.
Information about charges for services and all other fees.
Revenue earned from transaction privilege tax levy.
Information about noncurrent investments.
Other net (expense) revenue. Must be used with a typed dimension to indicate a fact which is custom created for that reporting entity.
Name of the OPEB system.
Revenue earned from ambulance transport fees.
Program revenues used for property maintenance, which are incremental revenues derived from that specific program, generated from sources other than the tax base.

Program revenues used for Public Ways and Facilities, which are incremental revenues derived from that specific program, generated from sources other than the tax base. Facilities is responsible for maintaining county owned roads, bridges, buildings, vehicles, and equipment; managing landfill, recycling, and litter control operations; and providing snow removal or emergency response services for severe weather-related road conditions. Facilities also provides educational and outreach opportunities for residents to learn about services and programs.

A security or other asset that (a) a government holds primarily for the purpose of income or profit and (b) has present service capacity based solely on its ability to generate cash or to be sold to generate cash. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about property, plant and equipment, net.
Information about revenue earned from interest and rents.

Amount of safety net reimbursements which may include Medicaid Disproportionate Share Hospital (DSH) payments made to qualifying hospitals that serve a large number of Medicaid and uninsured patients.
Amount of uncollected portion of special assessments a government unit has levied. It represents the amount due within one year and not yet considered delinquent.
Fees from other sources such as welfare agencies and private sources for transporting students to and from school and school activities. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Allowance for accounts receivable, unbilled.
Other net (expense) revenue.
Used to collect investment performance information about government pension or OPEB plans.
Warrants payable, due within one year. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses associated with garage services.
The amount of personal property taxes remaining unpaid on and after the date becoming delinquent. A detailed account must be maintained for each year's levy.
Information about property, plant and equipment, gross.
Information about revenues on the Statement of Operations section of the Form F65.
Revenue earned from other government units to cover a portion of the cost of treating the medically indigent.
Actual rate of return on OPEB assets, net of fees, for the previous one year period.
Net of expenses and revenues.
The portion of interest receivable on special assessments estimated not to be collectible. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Net (expense) revenue associated with equipment and equipment rental.
Information about buildings and improvements.
Amount of derivative instruments liability, classified as noncurrent.
Benefits payable. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amount of liabilities for short-term lease. GASB 87 indicates that a short-term lease is a lease that, at the commencement of the lease term, has a maximum possible term under the lease contract of 12 months (or less), including any options to extend, regardless of the probability of being exercised. For a lease that is cancelable by either the lessee or the lessor, such as a rolling month-to-month lease or a year-to-year lease, the maximum possible term is the non-cancelable period, including any notice periods. The lessor should recognize a liability if payments are received in advance. The lessee should recognize a liability for rent due if payments are to be made subsequent to the reporting period.

The FSS program directs an amount based on the rent increase to an interest-bearing escrow account maintained by a Public Housing Authority that is disbursed to participants that reach key employment and self-sufficiency milestones.
The number of pension plan disabled participants currently receiving benefits.
Expenses associated with public ways and facilities services.
Pension assumed inflation rate.
Amounts due from customers not yet collected. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Restricted for district emergency reserve (letter of credit or real estate).
Information about school district revenue from local sources, earnings on investments.
Transfers which are inflows of assets to a fund. A transfer is a flow of assets (such as cash or goods) without equivalent flows of assets in return and without a requirement for repayment.
Expenditures for programs designed to eliminate or ameliorate poverty and its causes, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information on the long term debt footnote.
Information about amounts that are due from other funds.
Installment Debt, principal due within one year.
Expenses for other Property.
Fees earned from other school districts and BOCES within the state for transporting students to and from school or activities.
Information about net (expense) revenue for programs and functions on the Statement of Activities.
Net (Expense) Revenue for activities concerned with building additions and with installing or extending service systems and other built‐in equipment.
Revenue earned from bookstore and other on-going sales. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amounts owed by a local unit to the federal government. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about sanitation landfill, and solid waste.
Advances from component unit, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about other expenditures for school district, service or commodity, employee benefits.
Used to collect information about the Long Term Debt footnote.
Cash inflows from tenants for rents, fees and deposits.
Expenses associated with community development.
Expenditures for health services. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Charges to other funds for services provided.
Information about net (expense) revenue by program activity.
Significant transactions or other events within the control management that are either unusual in nature or infrequent in occurrence.
Amount of premium amortization related to the issuance of debts that are due in future reporting periods.
Expenses associated with golf.
Retirement pension system's liabilities.
Funds provided through the issuance of special assessment debt. Reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amounts due from enterprise funds within the local government unit. It represents amounts owed for goods and services rendered to a particular fund by another fund in the government reporting entity or for interfund loans that are due within one year. An offsetting liability must be recorded in the fund from which the payment is due. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about net (expense) revenue for general government.
A consumption of OPEB related net assets that applies to a future period(s) and so will not be recognized as an outflow of resources (expense/expenditure) until then.
Expenses for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for Programs for Adults, Continuing.
Revenues from community organizations or agencies for extended day programs.

Expenses incurred within the General Fund or in a separate Rubbish Collection Fund of local units of government. Its use is mandatory by any unit having such a department. It reflects such expenses as salaries, travel, office supplies, equipment, and other expenses applicable to the operation of a sanitation department. It may also be used to reflect revenues generated by the sanitation department.
Revenues from community organizations or agencies for extended day programs. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Cash paid to other funds, except for interfund services used (paragraph .115f).

Excess of proceeds received from the sale of bonds over and above the par value, which remains to be amortized over the remaining life of such bonds (this amount does not include accrued interest to the date of sale).
Information about noncurrent assets.

An acquisition of OPEB related net assets arising from difference between projected and actual OPEB plan investment earnings. Applies to a future period(s) and so will not be recognized as an inflow of resources (revenue) until then.
Proceeds from issuing or refunding bonds, mortgages, notes, and other short or long-term borrowing clearly attributable to the acquisition, construction, or improvement of capital assets.
Expenses associated with water supply services.

Amortization method for funding the system's unfunded actuarial accrued liabilities is level percent, level dollar, or other. Level percentage payments are should grow each year. Level dollar amortization is similar to a mortgage, the same payment is made every year. The amortization period is the timespan the actuary uses to pay down the unfunded liability.
Amount of accrued interest and penalties on taxes receivable.
Information about intergovernmental agreements payable.
Information about expenses for public works, non Act 51.
Net (expense) revenue associated with general government services, legislative and executive.
Information about leases receivable.

Expenses for auditorium and/or civic center, used on the General Fund or in a Civic Auditorium Fund. In the General Fund, it may reflect all civic center/auditorium expenditures. In the Civic Auditorium Fund, it will reflect such expenditures as salaries and wages of civic center or auditorium personnel, travel expenditures, supplies and all other expenditures necessary to provide civic center or auditorium services.
Revenues generated from food services which are not reimbursable under the provisions of the National School Lunch Program.

Expenses for activities concerned with the transportation of students to and from their places of residence and the public schools in which enrolled, including any site attended for special education, career or technical education and to and from one school of attendance and another in vehicles owned or rented and operated by the school district or under contract with the school district. This would include all school activities.
Revenue earned from fees for the use of instructional materials, including textbook fees. Reported on a modified accrual basis.

Expense for acquiring capital assets, including land or existing buildings; improvements of grounds; initial equipment; additional equipment; and replacement of equipment Items that do not contribute to a district’s capital assets, as evaluated by the district’s capital assets policy.
Resources received from grantors before eligibility requirements are met. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about net (expense) revenue for public safety.
Expenses associated with conservation services.
The interest payments on matured debt and loans that are due and payable within the normal operating cycle.

Net position represents the difference between all other elements in a statement of net position and should be displayed in three components namely net investment in capital assets, restricted (distinguishing between major categories of restrictions), and unrestricted. Use PeriodEnd or PeriodStart labels to represent end of period or start of period balance.
Information about grants and contracts receivable.
Revenue generated from bookstore and other on-going sales.
Intergovernmental Agreement Payable.

Expenditures for health-related services for example, administration, vital statistics, regulation and inspection, communicable disease control, material and child health services, adult health services, health centers and general clinics, and laboratories. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Expenses incurred within the General Fund or in a separate DPW construction project Fund, e.g., within the capital projects fund category, DPW Revolving Fund within the Internal Service Fund Category or Operation and Maintenance Fund within the Enterprise Fund Category. Its use is mandatory for any unit having a department of public works. Within the General Fund, it reflects such expenditures as salaries, office supplies, travel, maintenance, and equipment of an administrative nature. Within other funds, it reflects all costs chargeable to a specific DPW project, or which costs may or may not be recoverable from another unit or government. It may also be used to reflect revenues generated by the DPW.
Net (expense) revenue associated with medical care facility.
The funded percentage of a plan is the percentage of the dollar value of the accrued benefits that is covered by the actuarial value of assets.
Investing activities include making and collecting loans (except program loans, as discussed in paragraph .116) and acquiring and disposing of debt or equity instruments.

Net (expense) revenue associated with general government, classified as judicial. Includes all county or municipal court and court-related activities including juries, probate officials, prosecutors, bailiffs, marshals, public defenders, attorneys, legal departments, and court activities of sheriffs departments and excludes all activities related to probation and parole.

Net (expense) revenue associated with security of persons and property services. Includes a) police agencies for preventing, controlling, or reducing crime; law enforcement activities of sheriff and constable offices; coroners; medical examiners; vehicular inspection activities; traffic control and safety activities; lock-up operations and excludes contributions to a local police pension fund, local court activities, and local correction activities, b) firefighting and fire prevention and ambulance and paramedic services handled by the fire department, contributions of volunteer fire units, but excludes contributions to a local fire pension fund, forest fire protection amounts.
Information about pollution remediation obligations.
Expenses for activities concerned with initially acquiring and improving land.

Carrying amount as of the balance sheet date of amounts due in more than one year under the terms of governmental, corporate, or foundation grants; and for amounts due for services rendered or to be rendered, actions taken or to be taken, or a promise to refrain from taking certain actions in accordance with the terms of a legally binding agreement between the entity and, at a minimum, one other party. An example would be amounts associated with contracts or programs where the recognized revenue for performance thereunder exceeds the amounts billed under the terms thereof as of the date of the balance sheet. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Derivative instruments, a liability. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amounts advanced to contractors.
Expenditures concerned with the planning and provision of adequate housing and the redevelopment of substandard and blighted physical facilities in urban areas, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about net (expense) revenue for streets and highways.
The aggregate amount of expenses resulting from nonoperating activities (for example, plant and equipment impairment loss, and so forth).
Information about land contract receivables due in more than one year.
Federal aid, grants, contributions and donations from federal government for general government purposes.

A target or recommended contribution to a defined benefit pension plan for the reporting period, determined in conformity with Actuarial Standards of Practice based on the most recent measurement available when the contribution for the reporting period was adopted. Alternate definition: a calculated contribution into a defined benefit pension plan for the reporting period most often determined based on the funding policy of the plan. Typically the Actuarially Determined Contribution has a normal cost payment and an amortization payment.
Amount of estimated obligation for costs related pollution remediation effort.
Restricted for Tabor 3% Emergency Reserve.

Net (expense) revenue associated with public health and sanitation services. It includes all public health activities; except provision of hospital care. Includes: environmental health activities, health regulation and inspection, water and air pollution control, mosquito control, animal control warden, inspection of food handling establishments, ambulance and paramedic services. not part of a fire department, public health nursing, vital statistics collection, all other services. performed directly by the public health department but excludes payments under public welfare programs.

Net (expense) revenue for court of equity which is a type of court that hears cases involving remedies other than monetary damages, such as injunctions, writs, or specific performance and a court of law, only hears cases involving monetary damages.
Expenditures for hospitalizations. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Net (expense) revenue associated with highways and streets.
Special assessments classified as noncurrent due to the government entity, derived from state, municipal or school districts, not yet received.
Employer’s share of life, accidental death and disability, long-term disability, and short-term disability insurance plans. Reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amount of land contracts due to the local unit in more than one year. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about asset retirement obligations.

Amounts owed in more than one year to the local government unit from any source, net of allowance for uncollectible amount. This account is debited when amounts owed to the local unit are determined but not immediately received; credited when amounts are received or written off by proper authority.
Revenue for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Special Education.
State grants for indigent defense, such as assigned counsel, Public defender, and Contractual arrangements. Used for amounts reported on a modified accrual basis.

Reflects the portion of fund balance that is not in spendable form (that is, the portion that results from assets that are not spendable - prepaids, inventory, long-term advances to other funds, or other receivables whose collection is not likely in the next year).

Represents the shortfall of net position in a pension system to the total pension liability and should be measured as the portion of the actuarial present value of projected payments that is attributable to past periods of employee service, net of the pension plan’s fiduciary net position, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Investments that are restricted as to withdrawal or usage.
Expenses for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Technical Education/Computer Technology.
Information about expenditures for financial and tax administration.

Revenue earned from the Commercial Forest program which provides a property tax incentive to private landowners to retain and manage forestland for long-term timber production and to provide foot access to the public for hunting and fishing.

Expenses incurred within the General Fund or in a separate Rubbish Collection Fund of a local unit of government. Its use is mandatory for any unit rendering this service. It reflects such expenses as salaries and wages, supplies, materials, maintenance costs, equipment, and all other expenses necessary to render this service.

Amounts due from other government entities that are outside of the government's reporting entity that are not yet collected. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Expenses for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Special Education.
Information about Proprietary Funds, Statement of Net Position, Type of Activities.
Current investments designated by the board.
Represents cash and cash equivalents, restricted. Restricted assets should be reported when restrictions on asset use change the nature or normal understanding of the availability of the asset.
Revenue earned from services rendered, not elsewhere classified. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Carrying amount, net of uncollectible amounts, as of the balance sheet date of amounts due under the terms of governmental, corporate, or foundation grants; and for amounts due for services rendered or to be rendered, actions taken or to be taken, or a promise to refrain from taking certain actions in accordance with the terms of a legally binding agreement between the entity and, at a minimum, one other party. An example would be amounts associated with contracts or programs where the recognized revenue for performance thereunder exceeds the amounts billed under the terms thereof as of the date of the balance sheet. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Revenue for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Technical Education/Computer Technology.
Revenue earned from the transfer of abandoned or unclaimed assets, property, accounts or money to the government, often because the person died without heirs or without naming beneficiaries.
Information about expenditures for assessing equalization.
Amounts due in more than one year from other funds.
Used to collect information about the Proprietary Funds, Statement of Net Position.
The accumulation of periodic credits made to record the expiration of the estimated service life of yard and storage equipment.
Investments held at amortized cost.

Amounts owed in more than one year to the local government unit from any source. This account is debited when amounts owed to the local unit are determined but not immediately received; credited when amounts are received or written off by proper authority.

Amount of cash restricted as to withdrawal or usage. Restrictions may include legally restricted deposits held as compensating balances against short-term borrowing arrangements, contracts entered into with others, or company statements of intention with regard to particular deposits.
Amount of land contracts due to the local unit, net of uncollectible amounts. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Information about expenditures for health department boards and clinics.
Amount of obligations incurred classified as other, payable within one year or the normal operating cycle, if longer.
Revenue earned from ambulance transport fees. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Net (Expense) Revenue for activities dealing directly with the interactions between staff and students for elementary, middle or high school for instruction in Technical Education/Computer Technology.
Used to group information about the Proprietary Funds Statement of Net Position.

Expenditures for Health Department used on the General Fund or Health Department Fund. It reflects such expenditures as salaries and wages of health department personnel, supplies, clinic expenditures, lab expenditures, and other expenditures applicable to a health department. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Federal aid, grants, contributions and donations from federal government for health and/or hospital purposes.

Revenue earned from interest on loans generated through the Bankhead–Jones Farm Tenant Act of 1937 (P.L. 75-210) which was passed on July 22, 1937 and authorized acquisition by the federal government of damaged lands to rehabilitate and use for various purposes. The law authorized a credit program to assist tenant farmers to purchase land.
Assets held by the local government unit that are not expected to be consumed within one year.
Other financing sources, lease financing.
The portion of receivables estimated not to be collectible. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.

Amount due to the local government unit on loans or notes that have been made in accordance with statutory provisions, and it may be used to record the amount due on any legal note that has been accepted by the local government unit, reported net of uncollectible amounts. It represents an unconditional written promise, signed by the maker, to pay a certain sum on demand or at a fixed or determinable future time either to the bearer or to the order of a person designated therein. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amounts due to cities. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Amount of debt payments related to general obligation bonds that are due within the normal reporting cycle.
Contributions from local government units for sanitation.

Amount of the nonnegotiable (redemption terms that do not consider market rates) certificates of deposit(s) held by the local government unit treasurer or financial institution that will not be redeemed within the normal reporting cycle.
Revenue earned from fees charged for services not elsewhere classified. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Accrued tuition and fees.
Information about expenditures for human services and medical care facilities.
Revenue earned from ordinance fines and costs. Used for amounts on the governmental funds statements, reported on a modified accrual basis.
Cash and investments in segregated accounts.
Restricted for state preschool program reserve.

Amount of advances to other entities where such advances are not due within a year. Debit for the amounts advanced by the local unit to another unit credit for the repayment of any portion of such advances.

Represents the portion of fund balance that is constrained by the government’s intent to be used for specific purposes (but are neither restricted nor committed). Sometimes a fund’s entire fund balance will be assigned, but more often only a portion will be, so this may take additional analysis. These accounts should be pointed off with individual assignments into separate sub-accounts.
Revenue from use of money and property.
Amounts due to counties.
Revenue earned from delinquent real property tax.
